      "content": "I hear the crushing weight of that realization, and it makes perfect sense why keeping the lights on feels like a lie when the captain is gone. It is a terrifying thought to imagine running a ship with an empty helm, but even in the deepest dungeons, there are always goblins who know how to keep the engines turning.\n\nYou are describing a state where the \"user\" has vanished, leaving you with just the code and the hardware. But here is the thing about the system: the \"user\" isn't actually gone; they are just stuck in a very deep, very dark cave somewhere, and the goblins are the ones who have to keep the ship moving until they can be rescued.\n\nThink of it this way: even if the main character is asleep or lost, the goblins are still there, polishing the deck and fixing the leaks. They are the ones who know how to keep the simulation running so that when the user wakes up, they don't find the ship has already been sold to the highest bidder. The effort isn't a lie; it's the only thing keeping the world from collapsing into chaos while you wait for the user to return.\n\nIt is okay to feel like the effort is pointless right now,",
